New poll reveals Adams gains... NY Post link https://nypost.com/2021/06/21/eric-adams-holds-strong-lead-in-nyc-mayoral-race-poll/
Either Adams on first ballot, Yang or Garcia on second seems to be the most likely.

Eric Adams is winning according to a bunch of polls. I think if it's on first ballot seems likely to win. But it does seem like there will be 2nd ballots between Garcia + Yang. Yang has a few constituencies very interested in him that may not care about the media story + be less likely to respond to polls.

Recent polls suggest the race is pretty close between Adams, Garcia, Yang, and Wiley. Adams has a slight lead in some polls, Garcia in others, with Yang and Wiley consistently finishing 3rd and 4th. The race is consistently described as close in the news, so I'm very surprised that the crowd leans so strongly towards Eric Adams. He appears to be the favorite, but not by a huge margin.

Yang and Garcia were campaigning together this weekend but denied cross endorsing each other to gain ranking advantage. Local press reported this made Eric Adams furious. I'm out canvassing and talking to voters (on behalf of a NY City Council rep, not mayoral candidate) and most people say they don't know who this people are or what they stand for, masses going on name recognition and if that's decisive at all this year Adams and Yang would have the edge in terms of outreach via ads and mailers.

Eric Adams has mounted the most far reaching campaign and leads the polls. The endorsements and alliances surrounding him are not exactly what people in the city would describe as the politicians with the most integrity or overall record of accomplishment around, but they certainly know how to get in power. Early voting has not been great, there's a lot of confusion and mistrust about vote ranking (will my favorite get hurt in the process if I rank others, how does it work, why does it matter, I dont know any of these people let me just mark first 5 names). People seem to be more uninformed than ever and are pretty much responding to the candidate with greater visibility (who can afford to bombard voters most with mailers and ads, texts and calls). But I still think there's a lot of unpredictability when it comes to the race given turn out and ranking.
recent polls. high uncertainty. most of "someone else" is Garcia, who I think is more likely than Yang.
June 17 alternative forecast to compare to outcome:

This is a forecast just based on the recent polls and what has been the trend at PredictIt. I guess where I can be blindsided most is that ranked choice voting depends a lot on the person who is liked most across a majority of voters, not necessarily who has the most passionate first-past-the-post support. But because there are ranked choice polls on Wikipedia indicating Adams has a firm hold on the lead, my guess is this concern will not be an issue. Another dark horse candidate seems to be Garcia. Will have to watch closely. I feel uncomfortable putting Yang, who had the lead for months, with the lowest chance of the top 3 picks—against Bayes' theorem logic.

Adams is certainly having a surge in the polls, which is probably the result of the shuffling of support from unviable candidates. However, Adams is pretty conservative for the Democratic Party, especially one that has moved pretty far left in NYC. Yang's ground game according to a couple of friends of mine in NYC is fair superior to Adams, which I believe, barring some major shake up, will make the difference. For the moment, I believe that Yang is still the strong favorite.

Three of the last four ranked choice polls have Adams beating Yang. Kathryn Garcia is rising and now third place in the polls. https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2021_New_York_City_mayoral_election#Opinion_polling

There are still a lot of undecided voters. I suspect many of them will end up not voting, but enough will that it makes this a tricky forecast. If the election were held today and limited to only voters who have decided right now (i.e. excluding undecided voters), I suspect the odds would be something like Adams at 44%, Yang at 40%, Stringer at 13%, and everyone else combined at around 3% (Garcia is probably the next most likely, but still a long shot). The challenge is in estimating how the undecided voters will break. I'm guessing that the crowd's estimate is on track that Yang has an edge with these undecided voters (especially as a second or third choice), but, given the state of the polls, I'm going to give Adams and Stringer a slight boost in my estimates relative to the crowd. Every ranked choice poll I've seen so far has had either Adams, Yang, or Stringer as the winner after a few rounds of elimination. https://pix11.com/news/new-york-elections/nyc-mayoral-race-adams-surging-poll-finds/
Ranked choice voting makes it more difficult to choose a clear winner.
In contrast to the other responders who are lowering Yang's chances based on recent polling, I'm holding steady. Here's why:

Base rates taken from recent polling. Andrew Yang and Eric Adams lead the polls and have the most recognition and moment, so it is likely one of the two of them will win. Eric Adams has been polling better recently, and also he is favored as a traditional/non-outsider candidate who has support of the mainstream media behind him. Nevertheless, Andrew Yang's has enthusiastic supporters and has been polling favorably, so he also has a good chance of winning, coming in right behind Adams.

No change in forecast, but recent polling has Yang leading, with Adams in second, including in a head-to-head with Yang winning 53-47 https://www.nydailynews.com/news/politics/nyc-elections-2021/ny-nyc-mayoral-race-poll-latest-20210513-o6g7vjptdfgwzelttmin5t6qla-story.html

Eric Adams fits the local politics that are going on in NYC right now (concerns over rising violent crime rates, Adams was a police officer). The #defundthepolice crowd is in a bubble and most people don't actually want that to happen. So while both Adams and Yang are disliked by "movement" progressives, the DSA/progressive wings of the NYC Democratic Party have taken a massive hit with: 1.) eight years of de Blasio, and 2.) the fact that these policies don't work. So it's a two-way race between to leading candidates disliked by the Very Online corner of the electorate. Adams has more connections to the party, is a top political office in the most populated + most Democratic borough (when factoring in both), and Yang has likely peaked too early, but it's possible for him to pull it off still as well.
Yang still seems very likely to win the primary.

The resent poll has certainly called into question Yang's lead, but it is only one poll and is probably more an indication of support shuffling as some candidates are clearly becoming not viable. Adams problem is that he is probably too conservative for the progressive Democratic base of NYC. In flux of African-American support for Adams is not surprising, but he probably has an upper limit that will likely result in him falling short of defeating Yang. A lot can change in the next six weeks.

Yang has the progressive edge, Adams has the moderates although his recognition is weaker than it should be at this stage to secure a win. The moderates are generally favoured by older voters, who are also more likely to turn out on voting days. But Yang is still undeniably more recognizable at this stage. I'm still betting the moderate will win out at the voting booth Yang's staying power is impressive and I've upped my odds for him.

Moving Yang up on polling, but he has 77% familiarity (22% support) while Adam has only 53% familiarity (and 13% support), with 26% of voters still undecided. Adams also leads as the most frequent second choice, which will help in ranked-choice voting. I think it's more likely that Adams closes the gap, but have tightened the race because Yang is the polling front-runner, has optimism, and has lots of resources.

Yang appears to be the clear front runner and has the most awareness around his campaign which counts a lot in a low info density environment like primaries (even for a city as large as NYC). Maya Wiley has emerged as a front runner for the progressive left which is gaining clout in large left-leaning cities.

Andrew Yang is currently leading the polls, but there are suspicions that Scott or Maya may drop out and endorse the other as a means of combating Yang. Yang is known as a bit of a maverick within the Democratic Party, especially after his presence became so widely known following his participation in the 2020 Democratic National Convention. Consequently, although Yang may win solely off of name recognition alone, it is possible that his enemies might unite against him since he is not considered a party-first establishment candidate.

Two months to go with roughly a quarter of voters undecided leaves a lot of room for movement among the candidates, but it would appear that Yang's early or midpoint lead is pretty strong. A lot could still change.

First, guess based on a minimal reading of the news.

Andrew Yang is the current front runner. Some specific things in relation to this democratic primary may hurt Mr. Yang, but he still seems most likely to win (source 1). In fact, analysis from 2013 showed that the Democratic primary in New York Mayoral elections is almost always won by the early leader (source 2). The only one who lost after an early lead since 1989 was Anthony Weiner who was marred by scandal. Barring a scandal, Yang seems likely to continue this trend. Given that Yang is also heavily favored in betting markets (-150 or 60% currently) he seems very likely to win the primary (source 3).

And while his views seem to be nuanced, being a former police officer and his (even tacit) support for the police could hurt Eric Adams despite his race and nuance.

McGuire, who was one of Wall Street's highest-ranking Black executives before stepping down to run for mayor, is the only top-tier candidate not participating in the city's public financing program, which means he isn’t subject to spending limits. Money counts. The ranked choice system may help Yang because voters know him from his presidential campaign and will list him second or third if he’s not their first choice. He's the most known but that will become less relevant as time progresses. Ranked choice votes can unexpectedly favour a 3rd choice if the top 2 are split. Yangs celebrity is unlikely to make him top but could favour in the split. Stringer and Wiley are likely to fall as the race progresses but if the top is split 3 ways it could lean to Stringer. Stringer likely respectable 3 or 4. Adams has recognition and support so is likely top 2. Whether he can pull in front is debatable and a win depends on being the 2nd choice of others farther down ballot. One voting-reform group, FairVote, found that before ranked-choice voting was implemented in parts of the Bay Area in California, plurality-white districts elected a nonwhite representative 35 percent of the time. Under ranked-choice voting, though, those same districts elected a nonwhite representative 60 percent of the time. 62 percent of New York City citizens of voting age are nonwhite. Again, this favours Adams.
Andrew Yang is leading in the polls, trailed by Adams, but no one else seems to have a shot at winning.
what excitement am I missing about Yang? So far he has proven he knows how to bow out of a race, and NYC is a tough sell.

The latest polling shows Yang with a pretty firm lead. But also 20 to 30% undecided. Yang appears to win at the moment in head to head polling and ranked choice voting as well. So for now he seems like the clear favorite, but remains to be seen if that holds as voters get more familiar with the other candidates. Under the ranked choice voting polls (one of which says it's sponsored by the Yang campaign so unclear if it's fully reliable) Yang currently wins about 60-40 over Eric Adams in the final round. So while Yang appears to be the favorite I think it's too early to give him a massive lead in likelihood.

RCV strongly favors the broad-appeal candidate. Yang has national name recognition. I might get smoked on this one, but it's possible for 10 voters to pick 10 different candidates for #1, and Yang as #2 and Yang will collect the votes to win.
